article.headline: Charlotte doesn't collapse in Stinson's absence
article.linkText: Stinson gets scare in win over Shock
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Andrea Stinson was sprawled out
underneath the basket in pain. The Charlotte Sting's lead, and
promising season, appeared in jeopardy.

"Basically, it scared me," Stinson said of the hip flexor
injury she suffered with 17 minutes left in the second half of a
65-58 win against Detroit. "I didn't know what was going on. I'd
never had something happen like that before.

"But it's just a strain."

Tammy Sutton-Brown scored 17 points and Stinson added 14 for the
fourth straight win for the Sting (12-6). They moved into first
place in the Eastern Conference, one-half game ahead of the Shock
(10-5).

Stinson, who has started all 204 Sting games, said she expects
to recover after a week off for the All-Star break.

With Stinson on the sideline, Detroit went on a 15-5 run to cut
Charlotte's lead to 45-42 on Cheryl Ford's free throw with 7:22
remaining.

Charlotte responded with a 9-1 spurt capped by a 3-pointer by
Stinson's replacement, Charlotte Smith-Taylor, and hung on to
improve to 3-0 against Detroit this season.

Ford scored a career-high 20 points and Swin Cash and Deanna
Nolan added 11 apiece for the Shock, who have lost four of six.

"I think our defense was tremendous," Ford said. "But we
scored 58 points. You can't win in this league scoring 58 points."

The Sting missed 15 of their first 19 shots, six on blocked
shots, as Detroit took a 17-8 lead. Stinson led a 26-3 charge with
10 points, helping Charlotte take a 34-20 lead. The Shock made just
one field goal and committed eight turnovers during the 10-minute
spurt.

Detroit finished with a team-record 11 blocked shots, but
committed 22 turnovers.

"Turning the ball over is our No. 1 concern," Shock coach Bill
Laimbeer said. "We consistently turn the ball over 20-plus times.
Until we learn to take care of the basketball, we are not a very
good basketball team."
